{"title_page": "Fernanda Melchor", "text_new": "{{short description|Mexican novelist}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]]  -->\n| name        = Fernanda Melchor\n| image       = \n| caption = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1982|1|1|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Veracruz]], [[Mexico]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| education   = [[Universidad Veracruzana]]\n| occupation  = Novelist\n| genre       = [[Literary fiction]]\n| website     =\n}}\n\n'''Fernanda Melchor''' (born 1982, [[Veracruz (city)|Veracruz]], [[Mexico]]) is a [[Mexicans|Mexican]] writer best known for her novel ''Hurricane Season''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/feb/25/hurricane-season-fernanda-melchor-review|title=Hurricane Season by Fernanda Melchor review \u2013 intense and inventive|website=The Guardian|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/books/review/hurricane-season-fernanda-melchor.html|title=A Mexican Novel Conjures a Violent World Tinged With Beauty|website=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> for which she won the Anna Seghers Award and a place in the shortlist for the International Booker Prize.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/books/booker-international-prize-shortlist-kehlman-ogawa.html|title=Women Dominate Booker International Prize Shortlist|website=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nMelchor obtained a degree in Journalism from [[Universidad Veracruzana]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uv.mx/prensa/entrevista/en-mis-obras-hablo-del-veracruz-que-no-se-ve-fernanda-melchor/|title=En mis obras hablo del Veracruz que no se ve: Fernanda Melchor \u2013 Universo \u2013 Sistema de noticias de la UV|last=UV|first=Departamento de Prensa|language=es-ES|access-date=2019-01-07}}</ref> where she was Coordinator of Communication of the Veracruz-Del R\u00edo campus.\n\nShe has published fiction and nonfiction short stories and novels in publications as [[The Paris Review]], ''La Palabra y el Hombre, Exc\u00e9lsior, Replicante,'' ''Milenio semanal, Le Monde Diplomatique, Vice Latinoam\u00e9rica, GQ Latinoam\u00e9rica y Vanity Fair Latinoamerica.'' She began her writing career in 2013 with the publishing of ''[[Aqu\u00ed no es Miami]]'' and ''[[Falsa Liebre]]'', this last being her first novel.\n\n''Hurricane Season''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2017/06/12/actualidad/1497267306_195049.html|title=\"\u00bfDe qu\u00e9 sirve el amor cuando te est\u00e1s ahogando?\"|last=Ferri|first=Pablo|date=2017-06-17|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=2019-01-07|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref> ''-''a fiction novel based on the crisis of forbidden disappearance in her state, Veracruz, was featured as one of the best novels in Mexico in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chilango.com/cultura/entrevista-a-fernanda-melchor/|title=El frenes\u00ed de la escritura: una entrevista a Fernanda Melchor|last=Quezada|first=Jos\u00e9|date=2018-04-17|website=Chilango|language=es-MX|access-date=2019-01-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.letraslibres.com/espana-mexico/revista/por-fin|title=Por fin|last=Ortu\u00f1o|first=Antonio|website=Letras Libres|language=es|access-date=2019-01-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/es/2017/12/17/los-libros-de-ficcion-de-2017-una-seleccion-iberoamericana/|title=Los libros de ficci\u00f3n de 2017: una selecci\u00f3n iberoamericana|last=Carri\u00f3n|first=Jorge|date=2017-12-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-01-07|language=es-MX|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> It has been translated to German and English by Sophie Hughes. The novel has been shortlisted for the 2020 International Booker Prize.\n\nIn 2015 she was included in a Conaculta's anthology as one of the featured Mexican authors under 40 years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gatopardo.com/cultura/libros/temporada-de-huracanes-fernanda-melchor-escritora-mexicana/|title=Temporada de huracanes, la nueva novela de Fernanda Melchor|last=Maz\u00f3n|first=Selene|date=2017-06-26|website=Gatopardo|language=es|access-date=2019-01-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 she won the PEN Mexico Award for Literary and Journalistic Excellence<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/cultura/dan-premio-de-excelencia-periodistica-adriana-malvido-columnista-de-el-universal|title=Dan premio de excelencia period\u00edstica a Adriana Malvido, columnista de EL UNIVERSAL|date=2018-04-23|website=El Universal|language=es|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 she won the [[International Literature Award]] as well as the [[Anna Seghers-Preis]] along with the German writer Joshua Gross.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.berlin.de/tickets/literatur/nachrichten/5771717-3038603-annasegherspreis-fuer-fernanda-melchor-u.html|title=Anna-Seghers-Preis f\u00fcr Fernanda Melchor und Joshua Gro\u00df|website=berlin.de|language=de|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* ''Aqu\u00ed no es Miami'' (2013)\n* ''Falsa liebre'' (2013)\n* ''Hurricane Season'' (2017)\n\n== Recognitions ==\n\n* Winner of the First Essay Contest on Lynching by the [[National Human Rights Commission (Mexico)|CNDH]], 2002\n* Winner of the Literary Virtuality Casa de Letras, National Autonomous University of Mexico, 2007\n* Winner of the Journalism Award of the Journalism Foundation Rub\u00e9n Pabello Acosta, 2009\n* Winner of the Chronicle National Award Dolores Guerrero, 2011\n* Winner of the Pen Club Prize for Journalistic and Literary Excellence, 2018\n* Winner of the [[International Literature Award]], 2019\n* Winner of the [[Anna Seghers-Preis]], 2019 for ''Hurricane Season''\n* Shortlisted for the International Booker Prize 2020 for ''Hurricane Season''\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Melchor, Fernanda}}\n[[Category:Mexican women novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Veracruz]]\n[[Category:21st-century Mexican women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Mexican writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century novelists]]\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mexican novelist}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]]  -->\n| name        = Fernanda Melchor\n| image       = \n| caption = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1982|1|1|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Veracruz]], [[Mexico]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| education   = [[Universidad Veracruzana]]\n| occupation  = Novelist\n| genre       = [[Literary fiction]]\n| website     =\n}}\n\n'''Fernanda Melchor''' (born 1982, [[Veracruz (city)|Veracruz]], [[Mexico]]) is a [[Mexicans|Mexican]] writer best known for her novel ''Hurricane Season''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/feb/25/hurricane-season-fernanda-melchor-review|title=Hurricane Season by Fernanda Melchor review \u2013 intense and inventive|website=The Guardian|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/books/review/hurricane-season-fernanda-melchor.html|title=A Mexican Novel Conjures a Violent World Tinged With Beauty|website=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> for which she won the Anna Seghers Award and a place in the shortlist for the International Booker Prize.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/books/booker-international-prize-shortlist-kehlman-ogawa.html|title=Women Dominate Booker International Prize Shortlist|website=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nMelchor obtained a degree in Journalism from [[Universidad Veracruzana]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uv.mx/prensa/entrevista/en-mis-obras-hablo-del-veracruz-que-no-se-ve-fernanda-melchor/|title=En mis obras hablo del Veracruz que no se ve: Fernanda Melchor \u2013 Universo \u2013 Sistema de noticias de la UV|last=UV|first=Departamento de Prensa|language=es-ES|access-date=2019-01-07}}</ref> where she was Coordinator of Communication of the Veracruz-Del R\u00edo campus.\n\nShe has published fiction and nonfiction short stories and novels in publications as [[The Paris Review]], ''La Palabra y el Hombre, Exc\u00e9lsior, Replicante,'' ''Milenio semanal, Le Monde Diplomatique, Vice Latinoam\u00e9rica, GQ Latinoam\u00e9rica y Vanity Fair Latinoamerica.'' She began her writing career in 2013 with the publishing of ''[[Aqu\u00ed no es Miami]]'' and ''[[Falsa Liebre]]'', this last being her first novel. \n\n''Hurricane Season''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2017/06/12/actualidad/1497267306_195049.html|title=\"\u00bfDe qu\u00e9 sirve el amor cuando te est\u00e1s ahogando?\"|last=Ferri|first=Pablo|date=2017-06-17|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=2019-01-07|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref> ''-''a fiction novel based on the crisis of forbidden disappearance in her state, Veracruz, was featured as one of the best novels in Mexico in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chilango.com/cultura/entrevista-a-fernanda-melchor/|title=El frenes\u00ed de la escritura: una entrevista a Fernanda Melchor|last=Quezada|first=Jos\u00e9|date=2018-04-17|website=Chilango|language=es-MX|access-date=2019-01-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.letraslibres.com/espana-mexico/revista/por-fin|title=Por fin|last=Ortu\u00f1o|first=Antonio|website=Letras Libres|language=es|access-date=2019-01-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/es/2017/12/17/los-libros-de-ficcion-de-2017-una-seleccion-iberoamericana/|title=Los libros de ficci\u00f3n de 2017: una selecci\u00f3n iberoamericana|last=Carri\u00f3n|first=Jorge|date=2017-12-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-01-07|language=es-MX|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> It has been translated to German and English by Sophie Hughes. The novel has been shortlisted for the 2020 International Booker Prize.\n\nIn 2015 she was included in a Conaculta's anthology as one of the featured Mexican authors under 40 years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gatopardo.com/cultura/libros/temporada-de-huracanes-fernanda-melchor-escritora-mexicana/|title=Temporada de huracanes, la nueva novela de Fernanda Melchor|last=Maz\u00f3n|first=Selene|date=2017-06-26|website=Gatopardo|language=es|access-date=2019-01-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 she won the PEN Mexico Award for Literary and Journalistic Excellence<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/cultura/dan-premio-de-excelencia-periodistica-adriana-malvido-columnista-de-el-universal|title=Dan premio de excelencia period\u00edstica a Adriana Malvido, columnista de EL UNIVERSAL|date=2018-04-23|website=El Universal|language=es|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 she won the [[International Literature Award]] as well as the [[Anna Seghers-Preis]] along with the German writer Joshua Gross.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.berlin.de/tickets/literatur/nachrichten/5771717-3038603-annasegherspreis-fuer-fernanda-melchor-u.html|title=Anna-Seghers-Preis f\u00fcr Fernanda Melchor und Joshua Gro\u00df|website=berlin.de|language=de|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* ''Aqu\u00ed no es Miami'' (2013)\n* ''Falsa liebre'' (2013)\n* ''Hurricane Season'' (2017)\n\n== Recognitions ==\n\n* Winner of the First Essay Contest on Lynching by the [[National Human Rights Commission (Mexico)|CNDH]], 2002\n* Winner of the Literary Virtuality Casa de Letras, National Autonomous University of Mexico, 2007\n* Winner of the Journalism Award of the Journalism Foundation Rub\u00e9n Pabello Acosta, 2009\n* Winner of the Chronicle National Award Dolores Guerrero, 2011\n* Winner of the Pen Club Prize for Journalistic and Literary Excellence, 2018\n* Winner of the [[International Literature Award]], 2019\n* Winner of the [[Anna Seghers-Preis]], 2019 for ''Hurricane Season''\n* Shortlisted for the International Booker Prize 2020 for ''Hurricane Season''\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Melchor, Fernanda}}\n[[Category:Mexican women novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Veracruz]]\n